Contrary to the statement in `@BeforeClass` annotation javadoc :
``` /** The @BeforeClass methods of superclasses will be run before those the current class. */ ```
The `@BeforeClass` annotated method of superclass is not called if there is another `@BeforeClass` is subclass.

```java
public abstract class SuperTest {
    @BeforeClass
    public static void beforeClass() throws Exception {
        fail("why don't you call me ?");    // never fails
    }
}

public class MyTestA extends SuperTest {
    @BeforeClass
    public static void beforeClass() {
        fail("Thanks for calling");     // fails here
    }

    @Test
    public void test() {
        fail("Failure expected from MyTestA.beforeClass()");  
    }
}

public class MyTestB extends SuperTest {
    @BeforeClass
    public static void beforeClass() {
    }

    @Test
    public void test() {
        fail("Failure expected from SuperTest.beforeClass()");    // fails here
    }
}

```

The class `org.junit.runner.notification.RunNotifier` contains the following code:

	private final List<RunListener> fListeners= 
		Collections.synchronizedList(new ArrayList<RunListener>());
	...
	private abstract class SafeNotifier {
		void run() {
			synchronized (fListeners) {
				for (Iterator<RunListener> all= fListeners.iterator(); all.hasNext();)
					try {
						notifyListener(all.next());
					} catch (Exception e) {
						all.remove(); // Remove the offending listener first to avoid an infinite loop
						fireTestFailure(new Failure(Description.TEST_MECHANISM, e));
					}
			}
		}
		
		abstract protected void notifyListener(RunListener each) throws Exception;
	}
	...
	public void fireTestFailure(final Failure failure) {
		new SafeNotifier() {
			@Override
			protected void notifyListener(RunListener each) throws Exception {
				each.testFailure(failure);
			};
		}.run();
	}

The synchronization on `fListeners` is insufficient to avoid a `ConcurrentModificationException` because of the inherent recursion of the construct. The following unit test demonstrates the issue:

	final RunListener decentListener = new RunListener();
	final RunListener faultyListener = new RunListener() {
		public void testFailure(Failure failure) {
			throw new RuntimeException();
		}
	};

	final RunNotifier notifier = new RunNotifier();
	notifier.addListener(faultyListener);
	notifier.addListener(decentListener);
	notifier.addListener(faultyListener);
	notifier.fireTestFailure(null);

(Note that this will throw an `IllegalStateException`, because the `ConcurrentModificationException` is caught and followed by yet another call to `all.remove()`.)

N.B.: I did see [Issue 209](https://github.com/KentBeck/junit/issues/209), but filed a separate ticket because this problem seems to be sufficiently distinct.

Resolves the problem of keeping in sync AllTests suite with actual list of test classes.
Example:

```java
@RunWith(Scan.class)
@Package("tests.package")
public class Foo {
}
```

or

```java
@RunWith(Scan.WithCategories.class)
@Package("tests.package")
@IncludeCategory(A.class)
public class Bar {
}
```
